  "referred_to_by": [
    {
      "type": "LinguisticObject",
      "content": "This is an extraordinarily rare **gold striking** of a coin normally produced in silver — a quarter guilder (5 stuivers) of the Province of Holland, dated 1692. Gold strikings (*gouden afslagen*) are off-metal presentation pieces produced in tiny numbers (sometimes just one or two) for dignitaries or mint officials, using the standard silver-coin dies. They are among the rarest and most valuable items in Dutch numismatics; comparable gold strikings have sold at auction for **€180,000–€245,000**. The dies were engraved by **Daniël Drappentier** (1643–1714), Engraver General of Holland, West Friesland, Zeeland, and Utrecht, and the coin was produced at the Dordrecht mint under mint master **Mattheus Sonnemans**. It was bequeathed to Teylers in 1896 by **Adriaan Justus Enschedé** — owner of the famous Joh. Enschedé printing firm, printers of Dutch banknotes since 1814.",
      "classified_as": [
        {
          "id": "http://vocab.getty.edu/aat/300411780",
          "_label": "description"
        }
